Tested in a Framework 4.7.2 console application, but probability is high the bug is universal.
```c#
void foo() {
  var smth;
  try { smh = ...; }
  catch (Exception) { Environment.Exit(1); }
  // try using smth here
```
That code results in an erroneous CS0165 "Use of unassigned local variable" compiler error.

The compiler needs to be taught that `Environment.Exit` is an even harder terminator than `return`. While I haven't checked, there might be similar functionality in Thread that would need the same treatment.

Note to any CLR maintainers reading this:
While it could be hacked around at the library level by adding a `NoReturnAttribute`, this really is a lower-level `noreturn` that belongs at the CLR level. For inspiration, see Microsoft C/C++ extension `__declspec(noreturn)`.

**Version Used**: 16.6 Preview 3

